04826nam a22007335i 9780674735651DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979743592  a97806747356517 a10.4159/harvard.97806747356512doi  a(DE-B1597)427383  a(OCoLC)894987337  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a940.3562231 aFawaz, Leila Tarazi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Land of Aching Hearts :bThe Middle East in the Great War /cLeila Tarazi Fawaz. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (364 p.) :b18 halftones, 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tNote on Transliteration -- tNote on Exchange Rates -- tIntroduction -- t1. A Changing Middle East -- t2. The Empire at War -- t3. Living the Great War -- t4. Entrepreneurs and Profiteers -- t5. The Soldiering Experience -- t6. South Asians in the War -- t7. Cooperation and Disaffection -- tEpilogue: War Memory -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Great War transformed the Middle East, bringing to an end four hundred years of Ottoman rule in Arab lands while giving rise to the Middle East as we know it today. A century later, the experiences of ordinary men and women during those calamitous years have faded from memory. A Land of Aching Hearts traverses ethnic, class, and national borders to recover the personal stories of the civilians and soldiers who endured this cataclysmic event. Among those who suffered were the people of Greater Syria—comprising modern Syria, Lebanon, Jordan, Israel, and Palestine—as well as the people of Turkey, Iraq, and Egypt. Beyond the shifting fortunes of the battlefield, the region was devastated by a British and French naval blockade made worse by Ottoman war measures. Famine, disease, inflation, and an influx of refugees were everyday realities. But the local populations were not passive victims. Fawaz chronicles the initiative and resilience of civilian émigrés, entrepreneurs, draft-dodgers, soldiers, villagers, and townsmen determined to survive the war as best they could. The right mix of ingenuity and practicality often meant the difference between life and death. The war’s aftermath proved bitter for many survivors. Nationalist aspirations were quashed as Britain and France divided the Middle East along artificial borders that still cause resentment. The misery of the Great War, and a profound sense of huge sacrifices made in vain, would color people’s views of politics and the West for the century to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCivilians in warzMiddle EastxHistoryy20th century. 0aSoldierszMiddle EastxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xSocial aspectszMiddle East. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xSocial aspectszSyria. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2014z9783110370225oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067473565140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674735651423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674735651.jpg  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-a